<TITLE> Croatia slaps six-year sentence on rogue dealer </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 ZAGREB, April 18 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A former foreign exchange dealer whose speculative losses almost broke Croatia's fifth-largest bank was sentenced on Friday to 6-1/2 years in prison. A court in the Adriatic city of Rijeka also ruled that Eduard Nodilo, the trader who ran up losses of almost $100 million between 1997 and 2002, must compensate the local Rijecka Banka (eds: correct) for the losses, state radio reported. Five other suspects, including Rijecka's former CEO Ivan Stokic and another management board member, were acquitted, the radio said at the end of the trial which started in 2004. The prosecutors said during the trial that five years of Nodilo's transactions had "eaten away almost all of the bank's capital". The discovery of losses in March 2002 prompted a run on the bank and its owners, Bayerische Landesbank, handed back their majority stake to the government for a symbolic one dollar immediately after the scandal reached the public. The discovery of losses quickly turned the bearded, balding, chain-smoking Nodilo into East Europe's most notorious rogue trader, and earned him comparison with Nick Leeson, whose speculative trades brought down British merchant bank Barings in 1995. Croatia has since then sold its entire 85 percent stake in Rijecka to Austria's Erste Bank for a total of 155 million euros, including recapitalisati
